8ï¸âƒ£ Day Of Week Using If Else
--------------------------------------------------

Scanner Class for User Input:
- Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in); â†’ Creates a Scanner object to take input from the user.
- sc.nextInt(); â†’ Reads an integer value entered by the user.

Condition Used:
- if(num == 1) â†’ Sunday
- else if(num == 2) â†’ Monday
- else if(num == 3) â†’ Tuesday
- else if(num == 4) â†’ Wednesday
- else if(num == 5) â†’ Thursday
- else if(num == 6) â†’ Friday
- else if(num == 7) â†’ Saturday
- else â†’ Not a valid number (handles cases where input is outside 1-7)

Key Learning:
- The program maps numbers (1-7) to days of the week using if-else conditions.
- If a number outside this range is entered, it prints "Not a valid number".

Edge Cases:
- If the user enters 0 or 8, it correctly identifies them as invalid.
- The program does not handle fractional inputs (e.g., 2.5) since nextInt() only accepts integers.

Example Cases:
- Input: 1 â†’ Output: Sunday
- Input: 3 â†’ Output: Tuesday
- Input: 7 â†’ Output: Saturday
- Input: 8 â†’ Output: Not a valid number
- Input: 0 â†’ Output: Not a valid number

Closing the Scanner:
- sc.close(); â†’ Closes the Scanner object to prevent memory leaks.

Alternative Approach:
- Using a switch statement instead of multiple if-else conditions would improve readability and efficiency.

